 S1: BUILD DEPENDENCIES
 ----------------------
 Before you even attempt to compile the source, you'll need to make sure that
 your machine has the following packages installed:

 * CMake 4.3 or higher
 * Clang 20 or higher
 * [Just](https://github.com/casey/just) 1.56 or higher

 Third-party libraries, including libuv, are pinned Git submodules. Initialize
 them before configuring a fresh checkout:

 git submodule update --init --recursive

 S2: COMPILING AND RUNNING THE SOURCE
 ------------------------------------
 To compile the Battletech MUX source, 'cd' into the repo root and run:
 
 ```
 just build
 ```

 To run the self-tests:

 ```
 just test
 ```

 To install the binary into the `game/` directory, run:

 ```
 just install
 ```

 And to run the game, run:

 ```
 just run
 ```

 S3: COMPILE-TIME DIRECTIVES
 ---------------------------
 There are a number of compile-time directives available for you to further
 customize your game to your tastes. See [CMakeLists.txt](./CMakeLists.txt)
 for a full list.

 cmake -S . -B build -DBTECH_FREE_TECHTIME=ON

 To see the available options in your configured build:

 cmake -LAH build

 Common options include:

 * BTECH_ADVANCED_ECON=ON|OFF
 * BTECH_ENHANCED_LOGGING=ON|OFF
 * BTECH_COMPLEX_REPAIRS=ON|OFF
 * BTECH_FREE_TECHTIME=ON|OFF
 * BTECH_RENAME_HELP=ON|OFF
 * BTECH_CARGO_COMMANDS=ON|OFF
 * BTECH_MW3STATS=ON|OFF
 * BTECH_MOVEMENT_MODES=ON|OFF
 * BTECH_SCALED_INFRARED=ON|OFF
 * BTECH_OVERSPEEDING=ON|OFF
 * BTECH_ENABLE_ASAN=ON|OFF
 * BTECH_ENABLE_CLANG_TIDY=ON|OFF

 Most of these require rebuilding after reconfiguring:

 ```
 just install
 ```

 S4: GAME CONFIGURATION FILE
 ---------------------------
 If you look under /game, you'll see stompymux.toml (and its included
 aliases.toml). You'll need to look through stompymux.toml and change whichever
 options you want. 

 Note that you'll need to shut down and start the server for most of these
 config directives to take effect.

 S5: STARTING AND CONNECTING TO YOUR GAME
 ----------------------------------------
 Once your game is compiled and your game directory is populated, run this
 from the repository root:

```
just run
```

 This will start StompyMUX in the foreground with core dumps enabled. You
 should see the 'stompymux' process under the Linux/Unix command, 'ps'.
 Try connecting to the port you specified in stompymux.toml and see if
 you are greeted with a connection screen.

 IMPORTANT: The default wiz characters both have the same password:

 btmuxr0x

 You may connect with the #1 character (The god character, only use
 it when you have to change config directives or @set other players
 WIZARD) and the #2 character (Your new head wiz character). 

 You may connect using the two character's dbref like this:

 connect #1 btmuxr0x

 Note that the same password is used for both #1 and #2, you will
 need to change these using the @password command as soon as
 possible! 

 You should now be set to start tinkering! Good luck :)
